@michaelglass 

I think it's ok if you always use `if ENV['butts'].present?` but `if Figaro.env.butts`. 

Basically thanks to Figaro there would be no need for `blank?` test for boolean values.

@sheerun What do you mean by this being "nonsense"?

At one point I had added hash style access to `Figaro.env` but it would only duplicate behavior of ENV so I don't see it as necessary. There's nothing wrong with just using ENV if you like hash access.

As far as _case-insensitive_ hash access, I think it's too surprising. The only reason the current `Figaro.env` proxy allows case-insensitive access now is so that uppercase ENV values would not require uppercase method calls.

@johnvh I think you're using Figaro 0.7 rather than master, yes? In 0.7, `Figaro.env` is kind of a mutt. It represents a hash of the Figaro configuration values in `application.yml` but it also passes method calls through to ENV. In your case, `Figaro.env.to_h` is giving you the values that Figaro found in `application.yml`, but anything that actually looks into ENV will find your overridden value instead.

The forthcoming 1.0 release no longer gives `Figaro.env` a dual purpose. It will serve only to fall through to ENV with convenient method style access. Access to Figaro's configuration as it's found in `application.yml` will be available at `Figaro.application.configuration`.

I hope that clears it up. If you're looking for the values actually set to ENV, I recommend just using ENV directly.

