Ah, there's the issue! This isn't specific to `clipboard-polyfill`, but you have make sure that `clipboard.writeText` receives `clipboard` as its value for `this`:

    // Explicit `bind`:
    somePromiseThatReturnsAString.then(clipboard.writeText.bind(clipboard))

    // Arrow function
    somePromiseThatReturnsAString.then(text => clipboard.writeText(text))

    // `await` (requires being in an async function)
    clipboard.writeText(await somePromiseThatReturnsAString)

This isn't obvious, because many browsers now bind functions like `console.log` for convenience so that you don't have to do this â€“ but it's necessary in the general case. If you try it in Chrome, you'll see that `somePromiseThatReturnsAString.then(navigator.clipboard.writeText)` also fails.

I don't think it's a good idea to add a convenience to the polyfill that doesn't work with the API itself, so you'll have to use one of the approaches above.

