Animations are run asynchronously, so at the time you call `world.stop()` all the animations are set, but they haven't started, so that's why you don't see any changes. First thing I noticed is that your animations are note set properly. They have to look like this

``` js
item[3]
  .animate({
    translate: [vectorSize, vectorSize, 0]
  },  animSpeed, 'ease-out-quart');
```

so the second argument is not an object but an integer (animations time in milliseconds).

Then there are several ways to solve you `world.stop()` problems. First, you don't really have to stop the world. But if you really like to, you can add `world.start()` at the beginning of your `animaHandler` to make shire it's started and then `setTimeout(function () { world.stop() }, animSpeed * 2)` at the end of your `animaHandler`. So your final code should look like this.

``` js
function animaHandler() {
   //here are all necessary calls and variable definitions
   world.start() // only in case you haven't started it yet

  item[0]
    .animate({
      translate: [-vectorSize, -vectorSize, 0]
    }, animSpeed, 'ease-out-quart');

  // other animations

  setTimeout(function () { world.stop() }, animSpeed * 2)
}
```

